Let’s make anolini! ☀️ 
Made with love by 📷@pastasocialclub Anolini hail from Emilia-Romagna & are typical of Parma (but with many regional variations, of course!). They’re traditionally filled with meat, parmigiano & often breadcrumbs, then served in meat broth. 

I filled some of mine with whipped ricotta & others with a mix of spinach, cheese, lemon & nutmeg. Then simmered & served them in the last of my parmesan broth from the freezer. 👌
Spinach Pasta Filling

2 large bunches spinach, leaves only
1 1/2 cups whole milk ricotta
1/3 cup parmigiano reggiano or other hard grating cheese
Dash of freshly grated nutmeg
Zest of half a lemon
Squeeze of lemon juice
Salt & pepper to taste

Blanch the spinach leaves in lightly salted boiling water until wilted & vibrant, about 30 seconds. Drain & run under cold water to stop the cooking. Wrap the spinach in a clean dish towel & wring out as much moisture as possible. Finely chop.

Add the chopped spinach & cheeses to a food processor. Follow with the nutmeg, lemon zest, a squeeze of lemon juice, salt & pepper. Pulse to combine until smooth & creamy. Adjust seasoning to taste. Transfer to a bowl or piping bag & refrigerate until ready to use.
